<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1909-02-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1909-02-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="115" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d115">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 774/572.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Beaupré</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">The
                                        Hague</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1909-02-02"><hi rend="italic">February 2,
                                1909</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 103.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to state that on receipt
                            of the department’s cablegram of the 27th ultimo,<note n="1" xml:id="d115fn1">See telegram of Jan. 26 to Ambassador Reid.</note>
                            I immediately advised the minister for foreign affairs that the
                            Governments of Italy and Austria-Hungary had been invited to participate
                            in the deliberations of the Internationl Opium Conference at Shanghai
                            and that his excellency has this day acknowledged the receipt of said
                            advice.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">A. M. Beaupré.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>